1. Introduction: What is League of Legends?

League of Legends (LoL) is a multiplayer online battle arena (MOBA) game developed by Riot Games. Released in October 2009, League of Legends has been around for many years and has millions of players. League of Legends hit peak concurrent players of 8 million and its competitive scene peaked at 44 million concurrent viewers during 2019.

The premise of the League's primary game, Summoner's Rift, is simple: each game consists of two teams of 5 players where players are traditionally assigned a role. There are 5 roles, Top, Jungle, Middle, Bottom and Support, with various characters (champions) to pick from for each of the role. There are currently 161 unique champions which all have unique abilities. After each team picks their champions, players are sent to their respective regions of the map. During a match, champions gain levels by accruing experience points (XP) through killing enemies and minions that spawn in each lane and the jungle. Gold is also gained upon slaying enemies and enemy structures, which allow players to buy items. Items can be acquired to increase champions' strength and are bought in one's own base. Each match is discrete, so levels and items do not transfer between matches. The winner of each game is decided by whichever team breaks the opposing team's base structure (nexus) first. More info found here.

Summoner's Rift with Regions

League's World Champsionship Series (WCS/Worlds) is the largest annual competitive event for the game. The Worlds for 2022 started on September 29th and ended on November 5th. The event was hosted in North America and consists of games between 24 teams internationally. More information about the event can be found here.

In this tutorial, my goal is to tidy the Worlds 2022 data that was compiled by Oracleselixir who scraped data from all games throughout all events using League's match history features. The compiled data gives valuable insight into which champions were strongest in terms of win rate, kill-death ratio, and gold compared to the enemy in the same lane. These stats are used to predict which champions performed well based on their stats, as well as predict whether or not a team is more likely to win due to champion selection. Champions are all unique, and each are usually assigned to their own roles. This implies various champions will gain more xp, gold, and kills overall due to their selected role. For readers unfamiliar with League, I hope this sparks interest in potentially watching the competitive scene or even playing the game by giving insight on which champions may be particularly strong. For experienced players, I hope to show interesting statistics and further insight into the nail-biter finale of Worlds 2022.

2B. Modifying and Tidying the Data

First, we want to collapse the rows of the data to focus on primarily the Worlds 2022 event. This is done through taking only the data which has a column specifying the competitive league "WCS," which indicates the World Championship Series. Furthermore, some of the data had incomplete games when looking through the data, so I extracted only the data of the Worlds 2022 games whose data was marked as "complete" instead of having missing data.

In [3]:
#This data specifies the World Championship Series league for the LoL Worlds 2022 event.
worlds = data[data['league'] == 'WCS']

#This data specifies the completeness of data, dropping the games without properly compiled data.
worlds_complete = worlds[worlds['datacompleteness'] == 'complete']

Removing redundant and useless data

I first started off by removing the useless data regarding the information of the game rather than the state of the game. Among these included the gameid, completeness of data, url, league, year, split, date, and more in the first few columns

Next, we need to compress the data about the game state, especially since many of the columns are either repetitive or too detailed to make a difference in the outcome of the game. To do this, we take the previous data table and further extract the important columns. Since we have data from both teams, any opponent data is redundant. I wanted to particularly focus on the data regarding kills, deaths, assists, major objectives during the game (baron nashor and the dragons), as well as the state of the game at 15 minutes. The reasoning behind the data at 15 minutes is because 15 minutes is typically when players start to leave their traditional roles and regions of the map. This means that at 15 minutes, we can see how well a certain champion or team performed against another during the first 15 minutes, which is also known as the "laning phase" during a League game.

Organizing and Modifying the data

So now that the data has cleaned out redundant and useless data for the most part, I want to extract two things: the data regarding a team's performance during a game, and the data regarding individual champion performance during games. Thus, I decided to split up the data into team data and champion data. I also noticed some data was all 0 in parts of each, so I opted to drop the empty data in the team and champion data tables.

In [6]:
#This data specifies each team's overall data compiled.
team_data = extracted_data[extracted_data['position'] == 'team']

#I decided to drop total cs, position, and champion, as total cs was not shown, and position/champion are irrelevent to a team.
team_data = team_data.drop(['total cs','position','champion'], axis = 1)
teams = team_data['teamname'].unique()

#This data specifies each individual champion's data compiled.
champion_data = extracted_data[extracted_data['position'] != 'team']

#Drops the all 0 data
champion_data = champion_data.drop(['dragons','elders','heralds','towers'], axis=1)

#Creates a new data table which compiles the champion, games won, kills, deaths, etc, and gets the # of games played
champion_data['games'] = 1
lst = champion_data.columns.values
newlist = lst[4:]
champs = champion_data.groupby(['champion','position'], as_index=False)[newlist].apply(sum)
champion_data = champion_data.drop(['games'], axis=1)

3. Data Exploration and Analysis

For this section, I want to see how impactful each of the columns are in terms of the influencing a win in a game, which is why I decided to first explore a heat map of the original champion_data table prior to combining champion data. This allows for me to explore and analyze which parts of the game are most impactful.

In [7]:
#Heatmap of Pearson Correlation of champion_data
plt.figure(figsize = (20,12))
sns.heatmap(champion_data.corr(), annot = True, cmap = 'Blues')
plt.title("Worlds 2022 Champion Data Correlation")
plt.show()

From looking at the correlation heatmap of our champion_data table, we can see in the results row, there is a greater positive correlation between kills and assists. Furthermore, there is a large negative correlation between deaths and the result of a game as well. This correlation in the heatmap implies that there is likely a correlation between the Kills to Death to Assists (KDA) ratio and the win rate of champions.

3A. Graphing Kills+Assist-Death vs. Win Ratio (by Position)

  • I used the champs data table in this case since I wanted to analyze each champion's collective kills/assists/deaths and win rate.

There are a multitude of champions and positions which the players of League can choose from, so I decided to further split the champs data table by position, as well as deprecate any champion data which had less than 5 games played total. Having less than 5 games played total could perhaps skew the data representation and cause an incorrect analysis of the data, especially since there would be under-representation of a champion. Furthermore, having less than 5 games played for a champion in a specific role could be due to an off meta (most effective tactic available) pick, where these champion selections are abnormalities to the traditional roles. I also calculated another value which sums kills and assists and divides by death, otherwise known as KDA. To obtain win rate, I calculated result divided by games, which is a champion's win percentage.

In [8]:
#Calculates each champion's respective KDA and win rate
lst = (champs['kills'] + champs['assists']) / champs['deaths']
lst2 = champs['result'] / champs['games']
champs['kda'] = lst
champs['win_rate'] = lst2

#Drops the champions with games under 5
champs_meta = champs[champs['games'] >= 5]

#Get the champion data based on each role: top, jng, mid, bot, sup
top = champs_meta[champs_meta['position'] == 'top']
jungle = champs_meta[champs_meta['position'] == 'jng']
mid = champs_meta[champs_meta['position'] == 'mid']
bot = champs_meta[champs_meta['position'] == 'bot']
sup = champs_meta[champs_meta['position'] == 'sup']

Each of the following graphs plots the various champions' kda vs win-rate and their regression lines for the 5 roles, top, jungle, mid, bot and support respectively. This allows to see champion win-rates according to their kda, and in terms of their respective lanes, shows how well each champion performs both in lane and after lane.

In [9]:
#Graphing top lane kda vs win-rates
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
plt.xlabel('KDA (Kills and Assists / Deaths)')
plt.ylabel('Win Rate of a Champion (%)')
plt.title('Worlds 2022 Top Lane Champion Win Rates')
plt.grid(color='lightgray', alpha=0.75, zorder=1) 
plt.grid(True)

#Creates a regression line for the kda and win_rate for top lane champions
kdaX = np.array(top['kda']).reshape((-1, 1))
win_rateY = np.array(top['win_rate'])
model = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)
model.fit(kdaX, win_rateY)

xfit = np.linspace(6, 0, 100)
yfit = model.predict(xfit[:, np.newaxis])

plt.plot(xfit, yfit)
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.xlim(1,5)

#Plots the respective champion data points for the graph
for c in top['champion'].unique():
    temp = top[top['champion'] == c]
    kda = temp['kda']
    win_rate = temp['win_rate']
    plt.scatter(kda, win_rate, color=np.random.rand(3,), label=c)
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1,1), loc=2);

Purpose of the Plots:

In terms of the plots, you could possibly analyze the regression line and find the residuals of points according to the regression line. However, some champion win rates are still somewhat outliers compared to the primary cluster of each group. For example, Yuumi the support champion boasts about a win rate of .825 with a KDA of over 10. This places Yuumi below the regression line, which would have led to Yuumi being misrepresented as a less viable champion to play when Yuumi's win rate is well above the expected .50.

As such, I primarily analyzed the raw win rates for the champions further out, and focused on the residual for plot points closer to the main cluster points. With this in mind, I found out the following:

Analysis of the best Champions:

Although the various KDAs and win rates of champions may differ due to other factors, such as a team's composition of champions and overall playstyle, these champions have been seen playing exceptionally well during Worlds 2022. What is interesting infact is how some of these champions are not traditional champions in these roles, as well as how other champions are commonly viewed by the community as "subpar" or "weak" when played normally.

In particular, Yone was played countless times in Top, and Maokai was played countless times in Jungle. Both have overall win rates of over .50, and are actually non-traditional champions for these roles. Riot Games had initially built and released Maokai to be played as a tank, somebody who absorbs damage from a team's crucial members. Tanks are traditionally played Top, but Maokai was seen performing exceptionally well in the Jungle. Furthermore, Yone, an assassin type champion, was designed to be played in Mid lane rather than in the Top lane. This perhaps could give insight into Maokai and Yone's strengths outside of their traditional positions.

Lastly, another champion to note is Rell. Rell is typically viewed down upon by the community due to the champion's reliance on assistance from allies. As a support champion, Rell's purpose is to tank damage for allies, as well as provide crowd control (cc). CC interrupts enemies and allows for teamates to deal damage to the enemies during the interrupt. Rell's win rate is typically not as high as the .70 we can see from the Worlds 2022 games. This likely is due to the smaller pool of games played, but another factor could be that the competitive scene of League requires constant communication with allies. This means that champions such as Rell are much more effective due to the presence of communication with allies, allowing for these various supports to be played much more effectively.

3B. Predicting Games Won/Lost (by Team)

  • I used the team win and loss data table in this case since I wanted to analyze predicting which team won or lost which game according to the Worlds 2022 games.

Worlds 2022, especially during its quarter-finals, semi-finals, and finals, consisted of many close games which were not exactly as one-sided as some of the previous year's games. As a result, I wanted to try and predict the winner of each of the Worlds 2022 games based on their respective in-game data. Through training a predictive model to identify which team won what game, I hope to provide insight on the predictability of the Worlds 2022 outcome where the team "DRX" won against "SKT T1" in the finals after going 3-2.

Training Win Data on Random Forest Classifiers and K-Nearest Neighbor Classifiers:

First, we separate the result, dropping it since it is all wins. We also drop the teamname categorical code data and set that as the y, setting everything else as our x. This allows us to split our Win Data into training and test sets of size .3.

In [15]:
#This is for the Win Data
X = team_win_data.drop(['result','teamname'], axis=1)
y = team_win_data['teamname']
xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 0)

Random Forest Classifiers on Win Data

Here I use the Random Forest Classifiers (RFC), training the model with the training data. After the RFC model is trained, we take the test set of data and create a prediction set of predicted y outcomes, which are the team values to determine which of the 26 teams won which game. Note that there are 26 instead of the initially mentioned 24, and this is due to the initial knockout rounds to determine which of the teams filled in the remaining slots to procure a total of 24 teams for Worlds 2022. At the end, I printed the initial accuracy of RFC predicting the data, and then a 5-fold cross validation for the RFC, printing its accuracy as well.

In [16]:
#Random Forest Classifier
rfc = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = 1, max_features = 'sqrt', n_jobs = 1)

#Trains the decision tree classifier with the training set
rfc.fit(xtrain, ytrain)

#Predicts the classifications of the decision tree classifier based on the test set
ypred = rfc.predict(xtest)

#Prints accuracy at classifying test set of teams who won which game
acc = accuracy_score(y_true=ytest, y_pred=ypred)
print(acc)

#5 fold cross validation for the Random Forest Classifier
scores1 = cross_val_predict(rfc, X, y, cv=5)
acc1 = accuracy_score(y_true=y, y_pred=scores1)
print(acc1)

Analysis:

Although all of the accuracies are very low, it is somewhat to be expected when working with 26 different possible identifiers and a small data set. The fact that the Win Data could obtain an accuracy of over .10 with both RFC and KNN is somewhat astonishing. This means that, with the data input from the many games, there is a higher chance for predictive algorithms to determine which team won what game than blind guessing. This result, although it may not be as exciting, is interesting due to Riot Games allowing players to predict the brackets and game winners when Worlds 2022 was taking place. Both algorithms have a higher chance of selecting the correct team for the winner of Worlds 2022 than players blindly guessing would.

One strange thing to note is the Lose Data, where neither algorithm could obtain an initial accuracy of above .05, but still obtained an accuracy higher than blind guessing a 1/26. This means that, although the predictive algorithms may be somewhat useful in predicting the winners of certain games, that the predictive algorithms are not as useful at predicting the losing teams of the various games. Another issue to note is that the 5-fold cross validation may not be exact due to some teams only having the opportunity to play a single game (this is a result of the initial knockout brackets to fill the 24 slots). This may have attributed to an inaccuracy in the 5-fold cross validation accuracy.

4. Conclusion and Further Steps

Although League of Legends has millions of players everyday playing the game and even more watching the competitive scene, each and every one of their games are temporarily recorded in their match history database. It is rare to encounter a MOBA game of such complexity to provide in-depth statistics at the level League of Legends does. Even from one competitive event alone, I learned a lot about the game through the scraped data and covered quite a bit of the data science pipeline our class experienced throughout the data class of CMSC320. What I have covered is only a fraction of the thousands of games played by players, with each game having its own unique result and gameplay. There is a degree of complexity to League of Legends that cannot be boiled down to raw statistical numbers, but the champion win rate data does provide valuable insight for both inexperienced and experienced players. Even if League is not the type of game you might play, a lot of the processing of data could be applied to other datasets. Data science, at its core, is all about cleaning and modifying data so that data analysis could be done on the dataset through plots, predictive algorithms, and more.

If you are interested in League of Legends or the data behind League of Legends' games, there is much more to explore and digest. I primarily focused on the Worlds 2022 event (WCS), which is only one of the hundreds of events available in the competitive match history dataset. More analyses could be performed on other leagues, the compilation of all competitive leagues, as well as comparing champion/team performance by date. If you play League, you know that Riot Games updates the game bi-weekly with new changes to items, champions, and more. This means that various champions and items are always changing, so no game is the exact same across even the period of a month. This tutorial was just a small insight of the vast amounts of in-game match history data that League of Legends has to offer to be analyzed, and I hope it was just as interesting for you as it was for me!
